©Sarah Breedlove–who later would come to be known as Madam C. J. Walker–was born on December 23, 1867 near Delta, Louisiana cotton plantation where her parents, Owen and Minerva Anderson Breedlove, had been enslaved before the end of the Civil War, Louisiana
youngest of 5 children, only one born after the emanicipation proclomation and therefore born free
1873 - mother Minerva Anderson dies
1875 - father Owen Breedlove dies
1867 + 14 = 1881 At 14, she married Moses McWilliams to escape abuse from her cruel brother-in-law, Jesse Powell.
June 6, 1885 - 18 - Her only daughter, Lelia (later known as A’Lelia Walker) was born on June 6, 1885. 
1887 - 20 - husband dies, moves to St. Louis to join 4 brothers who were barbers
1890s - in her 20s, suffers from scalp ailment that causes her to lose most of her hair
consulted with brothers for advice and experiments with home-made and store brought products
starts using products from Annie Malone
1894 - marries John Davis
1905 - brothers die, separates from 3nd husband John Davis
July 1905 - 38 - moved to Denver CO as a sales agent for Malone
married 3rd (2nd??) husband, Charles Joseph Walker
changes her name to Madam CJ Walker
begins selling Madam Walker's Wonderul Hari Grower
scalp conditioning and healing formula, which she says came to her in a dream
Madam Walker’s five original products were Madam Walker’s Wonderful Hair Grower, Temple Salve, Tetter Salve, Vegetable Shampoo and Glossine.
Sept. 1906 - traveled for 1.5 years through South and Southeast, selling door to door, demonstrations in churches and lodges, and devising her sales and marketing strategies
1908 - 41 - moved to Pittsburgh where she opened Lelia College to train Walker "hair culturists"
1910 - divorces Charles Joseph Walker
1910 - 43 - settles in Indianapolis, Indiana, built a factory, hair and manicure salon and another training school
less than a year later, made headlines in the black press for $1,000 contribution to the building fund of the "colored" Indianapolis Senate Avenue YMCA
1913 - 46 - traveled to Central America and Caribbean to expand the business
same year, daughter A'Lelia moves into Harlem townhouse and Walker Salon, designed by black architect Vertner Tandy - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertner_Woodson_Tandy
1916 - 49 - Madam moves to NYC, leaving daily ops of the Madam CJ Walker Manufacturing Company in Indianapolis to FB Ransom, lawyer, and Alice Kelly, her factory forelady and former school teacher
continued to oversee the business and work in their NYC office
involved in Harlem's political and social life, makes a $5k contribution (equiv $72,700) to NAACP's anti-lynching movement
at the time, largest individual gift to NAACP had ever recieved
Madam CJ Walker Hair Culturists Union of American convention - one of the first national meetings of business women in the country
May 26, 1919 - 51 dies of kidney failure and other complications from hypertension at Villa Lewaro, her Irvington-on-Hudson, NY estate
Buried in Woodlawn Cemetary in the Bronx - https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodlawn_Cemetery_(Bronx,_New_York)
time of death, estate worth estimated value of $600,000 - $700,000 - equivalent of $6 - $7 million in today's dollars
total sales of compnay during final year of life reached more than $500K
combined value of personal assets and business was over $1,000,000
Will designated 2/3 of future net profits of estate to charity


